"'''Onward, Christian Pilgrims'''" is a 20th-century [[Christians|Christian]] [[hymn]] by David Wright. It was composed in 1982, is based on "[[Onward, Christian Soldiers]]", and was intended as a non-militaristic version of the earlier hymn.

== History ==
"Onward, Christian Soldiers" was written in 1865 and uses [[New Testament military metaphors]] of [[Miles Christianus|Christians as soldiers]].<ref>{{cite book|title=God's Church Made Simple |first=James Edward |last=Smith |publisher=Lulu.com |year=2009 |ISBN=0557135710 |page=44 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-HfoAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA44}}</ref> In the 1980s there was a growing movement against the notion of Christian military references, leading to some churches in the United States dropping it from their hymn books.<ref>{{cite web|first=Ari L. |last=Goldman |authorlink=Ari L. Goldman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/20/nyregion/new-methodist-hymnal-is-shorn-of-stereotypes.html |title=New Methodist Hymnal Is Shorn of Stereotypes|work=[[The New York Times]] |date=1989-06-20 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, after the [[Falklands War]], David Wright attempted to revive "Onward, Christian Soldiers" as a pacifist hymn<ref>{{cite book|title=Aled Jones' Forty Favourite Hymns |authorlink=Aled Jones |first=Aled |last=Jones |publisher=Random House |year=2009 |ISBN=1409050777 |chapter=39}}</ref> while keeping its tune by writing "Onward, Christian Pilgrims" to the same tune.<ref name=tele>{{cite news |last=Howse |first=Christopher |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/10233544/Onward-Christian-Soldiers-Arthur-Sullivans-greatest-hit.html |title=Onward, Christian Soldiers: Arthur Sullivan's greatest hit |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=2013-08-09 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> [[Richard Ingrams]] informed the wider British public about the hymn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/aug/15/comment.richardingrams|title=This flock is too woolly|publisher=guardian.co.uk|work=The Guardian|date=2004-08-15|accessdate=2017-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicherald.co.uk/news/2014/07/31/the-organist-is-dead/|title=The organist is dead|work=The Catholic Hearald|date=2014-07-15|accessdate=2017-02-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/commentators/richard-ingrams-week-tories-ignore-the-big-issue-324967.html?amp|title=Richard Ingrams' Week: Tories ignore the big issue|date=2005-11-05|accessdate=2017-02-10}}</ref> The hymn was later included in [[Anglican]] hymn books from 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/text/onward_christian_pilgrims |title=Onward, Christian pilgrims |publisher=Hymnary.org |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/hymn/HONNA/408 |title=Hymns Old and New: New Anglican 408. Onward, Christian pilgrims |publisher=Hymnary.org |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> It also replaced "Onward, Christian Soldiers" in British crematorium hymn books because of concerns over "military imagery".<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Fletcher |url=http://www.burtonmail.co.uk/News/Crem-sorry-for-banned-hymn-row.htm?ID=476327 |title=Crem sorry for 'banned' hymn row |work=[[Burton Mail]] |date=2010-01-13 |accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref> The hymn was popular with some members of the [[Church of England]]'s clergy, with some clergy refusing to sing "Onward, Christian Soldiers" in favour of "Onward, Christian Pilgrims".<ref>{{cite news |first=Rachel |last=Newton |date=2001-11-17 |title=Vicar halts Onward Christian Soldiers |work=[[Liverpool Daily Post]] |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Vicar+halts+Onward+Christian+Soldiers%3B+'POPULAR+HYMN+IS+MILITARISTIC...-a080172571|publisher=archived at The Free Library|accessdate=2014-04-27}}</ref>

